    <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold mt-10 mb-4">Other Platforms Offering Free Trials Without Credit Cards</h2>
    <p class="text-neutral-300 mb-4 leading-relaxed">While See Guru is our top pick, several other platforms offer legitimate free trials. Here is how they compare:</p>
    
    <h3 class="text-xl font-semibold mt-6 mb-3">iTalki</h3>
    <p class="text-neutral-300 mb-4 leading-relaxed">iTalki offers a pay-per-lesson model, which means you can technically try the platform by purchasing just one lesson. They do not require a subscription or monthly commitment. However, they do ask for payment details when you create an account. The smallest purchase is one lesson, which starts around $5 for community tutors.</p>
    
    <h3 class="text-xl font-semibold mt-6 mb-3">Preply</h3>
    <p class="text-neutral-300 mb-4 leading-relaxed">Preply provides a free trial lesson for new users, but they require credit card details to secure your booking. You will not be charged unless you explicitly choose a subscription plan. This model is common in the industry, but it does mean providing payment information upfront.</p>
    
    <h3 class="text-xl font-semibold mt-6 mb-3">Cambly</h3>
    <p class="text-neutral-300 mb-4 leading-relaxed">Cambly offers limited free usage through their app and website, though access is restricted and popular times can be busy. For full access, you need a subscription. They require credit card details for signup, even for trial purposes.</p>
    
    <h3 class="text-xl font-semibold mt-6 mb-3">Verbling</h3>
    <p class="text-neutral-300 mb-4 leading-relaxed">Verbling connects you with tutors for one-on-one lessons. They do not offer a traditional free trial, but their pay-per-lesson model means you can start with a single session to test the waters. Payment is required per lesson.</p>

    <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold mt-10 mb-4">How to Get the Most From Your Free Trial</h2>
    <p class="text-neutral-300 mb-4 leading-relaxed">A free trial lesson is a valuable opportunity. Here is how to make the most of it:</p>
    
    <h3 class="text-xl font-semibold mt-6 mb-3">Prepare Before Your Lesson</h3>
    <p class="text-neutral-300 mb-4 leading-relaxed">Do not waste your trial lesson on small talk. Before your session, decide what you want to work on. Are you practicing for a job interview? Working on pronunciation? Preparing for a trip abroad? Tell your teacher your goals at the start of the lesson so they can tailor the session to your needs.</p>
    
    <h3 class="text-xl font-semibold mt-6 mb-3">Test the Technology</h3>
    <p class="text-neutral-300 mb-4 leading-relaxed">Use your trial to check that everything works properly. Test your microphone, headphones, and internet connection. Make sure you can hear clearly and that the video does not freeze. Technical problems can ruin an otherwise great lesson, so better to discover them during your free trial.</p>
    
    <h3 class="text-xl font-semibold mt-6 mb-3">Ask Questions</h3>
    <p class="text-neutral-300 mb-4 leading-relaxed">Your trial teacher expects questions. Ask about their teaching approach, how they structure lessons, what materials they use, and how they track progress. This helps you understand whether their style matches your learning preferences.</p>
    
    <h3 class="text-xl font-semibold mt-6 mb-3">Take Notes</h3>
    <p class="text-neutral-300 mb-4 leading-relaxed">Write down what worked and what did not during your trial. Did the teacher explain grammar concepts clearly? Were they patient with your mistakes? Did they correct you in a helpful way? These notes will help you compare different platforms and teachers later.</p>

    <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold mt-10 mb-4">The Bottom Line</h2>
    <p class="text-neutral-300 mb-4 leading-relaxed">Finding the right English tutoring platform is a personal decision. What works perfectly for one learner might feel wrong for another. This is exactly why free trials matter so much. By testing multiple platforms without spending money, you can make an informed decision based on real experience rather than marketing claims.</p>
